references: TableÂ I displays the interaction recognition results of the CEFHRI framework. Our assessment shows that the CEFHRI framework surpasses all other approaches, except for full fine-tuning, across all datasets and FL configurations. As reported in TableÂ I, the CEFHRI framework achieves satisfactory adaptation performance despite having significantly fewer trainable parameters than full fine-tuning. Moreover, the results presented in TableÂ I indicate that irrespective of the value of Î±ğ›¼\alpha, there is no substantial difference in the performance gap for CEFHRI. This highlights the crucial role of the pre-trained model in mitigating the impact of heterogeneous data. These findings are in agreement with recent studies conducted on image classification tasksÂ [46, 47].

references: One straightforward solution to reduce the communication cost is to use tiny video networks such as the X3D-S model [48]. Nevertheless, the architectures with low capacity are incapable of achieving satisfactory performance even with pre-training, as is evidenced in TableÂ III. In particular, X3D-S [48] could only achieve 30.8% HRI recognition performance on HRI30Â [12], while CEFHRI yields 84.6% accuracy for Î±=0.5ğ›¼0.5\alpha=0.5. Our comprehension is that models with low capacity are not effective in producing desirable performance under data heterogeneity scenarios. Consequently, the CEFHRI approach offers a practical remedy for mitigating the decrease in performance while still keeping the communication cost as minimal as that of smaller models, such as X3D-S, for the purpose of HRI recognition.

references: CEFHRI adapter is different in design from Â [20] and distinct in application fromÂ [19]. Firstly, the ST-adapter proposed byÂ [19] is specifically designed for frozen CLIP models, and its effectiveness in FL has not been explored. Secondly, the sequential implementation doesnâ€™t maintain the original features achieved by the frozen backbone. We argue that the parallel design of the adapter maintains the original features as the adapter branch is added parallel to the original MLP block and only scaled feature aggregation is performed. As shown in TableÂ IV, our analysis indicates that the parallel adapter structure outperforms the sequential design. As a result, we use the parallel ST-adapter design by default for the CEFHRI prototype, which distinguishes it structurally from that ofÂ [36].

references: In order to protect the privacy of the foundation model with lğ‘™l layers, we implement a model compression strategy by removing a specified number of layers, nğ‘›n from the ViT-B/16Â [35] model. The resulting compressed model is fine-tuned using knowledge distillation, with mean square error, under the supervision of the original model using Kinetics400Â [39] dataset for 20 epochs. The fine-tuned compressed model is then distributed to the clients as a point of reference. The clients then use this reference model to train the lâˆ’nğ‘™ğ‘›l-n adapters, which are later inserted into the server modelâ€™s last lâˆ’nğ‘™ğ‘›l-n layers. The results of our experiments indicate that knowledge distillation was essential in attaining the best performance. We also find that dropping the last nğ‘›n layers produced superior results compared to dropping the first nğ‘›n layers of the transformer model, which is consistent withÂ [38]. Therefore, the reported results in TableÂ V are generated using the strategy of dropping the last n layers for model compression. Here, we can observe that as the # of removed layers is more than 3, the performance drop is significant.
